WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:11.800
And let's move on to something a little bit more exciting, like an app with a plot.

00:00:11.800 --> 00:00:19.580
So this application here is pretty similar, but now when I change this slider, it's going

00:00:19.580 --> 00:00:23.959
to change, I think, the number of bins that go into computing this histogram.

00:00:23.959 --> 00:00:30.400
So you can see as I increase the number of bins, this histogram is going to have more

00:00:30.400 --> 00:00:31.760
staggered to it.

00:00:31.760 --> 00:00:37.959
So yeah, this one has a slightly more complex user interface.

00:00:37.959 --> 00:00:43.480
And notice as I make the window wider, this actually looks a little bit more like a sidebar

00:00:43.480 --> 00:00:50.560
than it does like an intro input panel or something like that.

00:00:50.560 --> 00:00:59.360
So this sort of functionality is provided by this layout sidebar from the UI sub package.

00:00:59.360 --> 00:01:08.480
So with the layout sidebar, it really wants like a sidebar panel and a main panel.

00:01:08.480 --> 00:01:15.419
And so on the left hand side here, I have the slider similar to what we had before.

00:01:15.419 --> 00:01:20.900
Another output text verbatim on the right hand side in the main panel and then a plot

00:01:20.900 --> 00:01:21.900
underneath that.

00:01:21.900 --> 00:01:29.500
And this example starts to introduce some reactivity concepts.

00:01:29.500 --> 00:01:41.180
So with this at reactive.calc, this is a decorator for defining a calculation that depends on

00:01:41.180 --> 00:01:49.379
some input values and then returns another value from some combination of input values.

00:01:49.379 --> 00:01:58.339
So this is like overly simplistic example that just reads the slider value and then

00:01:58.339 --> 00:02:05.300
multiplies it by two and gives this reactive calculation a name of R. So once I have this

00:02:05.300 --> 00:02:11.820
function defined as a reactive calculation, then I can read it just like I would read

00:02:11.820 --> 00:02:23.059
an input value inside of another reactive context like this rendered text output.

00:02:23.059 --> 00:02:31.059
So this is, you know, for all real practical purposes, this is essentially the same as

00:02:31.059 --> 00:02:42.059
just, you know, putting this expression into the read of R. But for more sort of sophisticated

00:02:42.059 --> 00:02:50.380
reactive web applications, this is a really useful construct for, you know, encapsulating

00:02:50.380 --> 00:02:58.300
like a chunk of a reactive calculation, whether it's, you know, performing a data summary

00:02:58.300 --> 00:03:03.979
or, you know, computing a model from some data.

00:03:03.979 --> 00:03:09.500
It's always a good idea to kind of put those steps into reactive calculations.

00:03:09.500 --> 00:03:15.460
Basically, it gives Shiny more information to do less work when it makes sense to do

00:03:15.460 --> 00:03:17.580
less work.

00:03:17.580 --> 00:03:23.300
So if you have like a big, you can define like a big reactive chain with like several

00:03:23.300 --> 00:03:31.300
calculations that depend on each other and if one of those calculations gets invalidated

00:03:31.300 --> 00:03:36.380
because the value is out of date for whatever reason, Shiny knows to not go back all the

00:03:36.380 --> 00:03:39.660
way to the top of that graph and recompute everything.

00:03:39.660 --> 00:03:46.860
It can kind of just say, I just need to do the last two calculations and then knows to

00:03:46.860 --> 00:03:49.740
do less work when it makes sense to.

00:03:49.740 --> 00:03:53.820
That is reactive calculations in a nutshell.

00:03:53.820 --> 00:03:59.539
And then to start showing you some different variations on rendering different types of

00:03:59.539 --> 00:04:05.100
objects in the UI, here's an at dot render plot.

00:04:05.100 --> 00:04:11.059
And these decorators can actually be used without parentheses or with parentheses.

00:04:11.059 --> 00:04:13.520
You can call it like a function.

00:04:13.520 --> 00:04:18.700
And that's particularly useful for something like render plot, which has additional arguments

00:04:18.700 --> 00:04:25.260
that you can specify like some alt text to put on this image to make it more accessible.

00:04:25.260 --> 00:04:30.179
Then, you know, you use it just like how you would a render text.

00:04:30.179 --> 00:04:37.019
You define a function and you can give this function a name which should match an ID in

00:04:37.019 --> 00:04:39.700
the user interface.

00:04:39.700 --> 00:04:47.299
And then inside of this function definition, I can do something like use matplotlib to

00:04:47.299 --> 00:04:55.260
create a histogram where the number of bins in this histogram comes from the value of

00:04:55.260 --> 00:04:56.260
the slider.

00:04:56.260 --> 00:05:02.980
At least currently, the way render plot works, you're going to want to always return a matplotlib

00:05:02.980 --> 00:05:11.260
object and then we'll know how to render that object into an image.

00:05:11.260 --> 00:05:17.700
I do also want to mention this render plot has the ability to understand more than just

00:05:17.700 --> 00:05:20.700
matplotlib objects.

00:05:20.700 --> 00:05:27.420
And I've actually whipped up this example app to demonstrate that.

00:05:27.420 --> 00:05:35.260
So I've at least laid out a few different packages here, but this is not...

00:05:35.260 --> 00:05:39.140
Render plot is not limited to just these packages.

00:05:39.140 --> 00:05:50.299
Essentially any package that builds on matplotlib or pill will be supported through render plot.

00:05:50.299 --> 00:05:55.260
A lot of what a lot of these packages will do will essentially build on matplotlib like

00:05:55.260 --> 00:06:01.100
plot nine, which actually gives like a more like a ggplot2 type interface to creating

00:06:01.100 --> 00:06:08.380
graphics and they'll essentially like subclass a matplotlib object, meaning like they are

00:06:08.380 --> 00:06:13.059
a special form of a matplotlib object.

00:06:13.059 --> 00:06:19.820
So as long as your object kind of, you know, subclasses matplotlib in some way, render

00:06:19.820 --> 00:06:22.739
plot should be able to handle it.

00:06:22.739 --> 00:06:30.700
So here's a plot nine graph that I've in the Shiny application, I've programmed to allow

00:06:30.700 --> 00:06:36.179
you to change like X variable, Y variable and color.

00:06:36.179 --> 00:06:40.700
We also support like Seaborn.

00:06:40.700 --> 00:06:45.820
You might be familiar with pandas plotting interface where you can essentially like from

00:06:45.820 --> 00:06:52.739
your data frame object called dot plot on that data frame object.

00:06:52.739 --> 00:06:57.700
And that will return, I think in like every case a matplotlib object.

00:06:57.700 --> 00:07:05.500
So you can just basically call dot plot and return that value and render plot should handle that.

00:07:05.500 --> 00:07:10.779
There's also like HoloViews, which supports all these different, you know, it also has

00:07:10.779 --> 00:07:20.459
interactive visualization capabilities, but you can also use matplotlib with HoloViews,

00:07:20.459 --> 00:07:25.059
X-Array and GeoPandas.

00:07:25.059 --> 00:07:31.260
So lots of different packages out there that build, luckily build on top of matplotlib

00:07:31.260 --> 00:07:34.739
and you can all use with render plot.

00:07:34.739 --> 00:07:39.480
So just to give you like a quick idea of what I mean there.

00:07:39.480 --> 00:07:46.380
So this is actually the source code for that application that we are looking at.

00:07:46.380 --> 00:07:52.059
So here's a render plot with Seaborn that's creating the scatter plot with the kernel

00:07:52.059 --> 00:07:56.579
depth density estimate on top of it.

00:07:56.579 --> 00:08:03.940
Plot nine was the more ggplot2 like interface here where I'm reading like an X input value

00:08:04.140 --> 00:08:06.459
and a Y input value.

00:08:06.459 --> 00:08:15.459
So whenever those change, Shiny will know to re-execute this function.

00:08:15.459 --> 00:08:18.459
As I mentioned with pandas, there's like a dot plot.

00:08:18.459 --> 00:08:24.260
So you can call that and return whatever that returns.

00:08:24.260 --> 00:08:27.299
HoloViews it's a little bit less straightforward.

00:08:27.299 --> 00:08:33.820
You can use like this render function from HoloViews that takes in a backend argument.

00:08:33.820 --> 00:08:41.299
So as long as you specify, I want to use matplotlib, then you can use it with render plot.

00:08:41.299 --> 00:08:48.739
X-Array is kind of similar to pandas in the sense that it kind of has like a similar dot

00:08:48.739 --> 00:08:56.460
plot like interface from its special data structure.

00:08:56.460 --> 00:08:59.780
And that also returns matplotlib objects.

00:08:59.780 --> 00:09:08.859
Again, GeoPanda is a lot like pandas where you can just call like dot plot.

00:09:08.859 --> 00:09:18.099
And then MissingNo, I think also returns matplotlib object, this matrix function here.

